abstract.gco:CharacterString: Statewide coverage of 1970 Places based on population data available from the U.S. Bureau of the Census. Population data is from the 1970 Census of Population

purpose.gco:CharacterString: To use in GIS systems for historical study and analysis This datasets is made available to interested persons through the University of Arizona's instance of Open Geoportal. It has been provided to assist educators, students, researchers, and policy makers in mapping and/or analysis applications.

credit.gco:CharacterString: Chris Kollen, University of Arizona Library

measureDescription.gco:CharacterString: Digitized city boundaries from the following maps: Avondale, Buckeye, Chandler, El Mirage, Gila Bend, Gilbert, Glendale, Goodyear, Mesa, Paradise Valley, Peoria, Phoenix, Scottsdale, Surprise, Tempe, Tolleson, Wickenburg, and Youngtown used Maricopa County Annexation File; Benson used Benson Arizona, 197-; Bisbee used City of Bisbee, Cochise County, Arizona, 1971 and Atlas of Cochise County, 1966; Casa Grande used City of Casa Grande, 1972; Clarkdale, Cottonwood, and Jerome used Clarkdale and Cottonwood 7.5' topographic quadrangle, 1973; Clifton used Atlas of Greenlee County, 1975; Coolidge used City of Coolidge, Arizona, 1968; Douglas used City of Douglas, 1967; Eagar used Eagar 7.5' Topographic Quadrangle, 1969; Eloy used Eloy, Arizona boundary map, 1974; Flagstaff used City of Flagstaff, a planning and zoning map for annexation and City of Flagstaff, 1970; Florence used Florence, Arizona, 1970; Fort Huachuca and Sierra Vista used Street map of Sierra Vista, Fort Huachuca. 1974; Fredonia used Atlas of Coconino County, 1971; Globe and Miami used Street map of Globe-Miami. 1971; Hayden, Payson, and Winkelman used Atlas of Gila County, 1975; Holbrook used Holbrook, Arizona 1965; Huachuca City used Official zoning map of Huachuca City. 1975; Kearny used City of Kearny, 1969; Kingman used Street map of city of Kingman, 1971; Luke, West Yuma, Williams (Maricopa County), Yuma Proving Grounds and Yuma Station used Arizona county subdivisions, census county divisions and places, 1971; Mammoth used Atlas of Pinal County, 1974; Nogales used Street map of Nogales, Arizona and vicinity, 1973; Parker used Plot of the Townsite of Parker, 1956; Patagonia used Atlas of Santa Cruz County, 1961; Pima used Town of Pima, 1971; Prescott used City of Prescott Annexation History, 2007; Safford used Street map of Safford, Arizona including Thatcher and Pima, 1970; St. Johns used St. Johns North and St. Johns South 7.5' topographic quadrangles, 1971 & 1974; Show Low used Show Low 15' topographic quadrangle, 1961 and Show Low North 7.5' topographic quadrangle, 1970; Snowflake and Taylor used Snowflake and Taylor 7.5' topographic quadrangles, 1970; Somerton used City of Somerton Annexation map; South Tucson and Tucson used Tucson Annexation Boundary File; Springerville used Town of Springerville, 1970; Tombstone used Special purpose map City of Tombstone, 1968; Willcox used City of Willcox, 1968; Williams used Atlas of Coconino County, 1971; Winslow used Atlas of Navajo County, 1973; and Yuma used City of Yuma Annexation map. For remaining places, used Geographic Names Information System database for point data. Created a 200 meter buffer around all point data in order to convert into polygons.

value.gco:Record: Accuracy ranges from ~10 meters (Scale 1:3,000) to ~1 km. (Scale 1:750,000)

description.gco:CharacterString: Dataset renamed from 1970_Cities.shp to Arizona_CensusPlaces_1970.shp by Ben Hickson with the University of Arizona Library. Metadata fields corresponding the Open Geoportal Working Group Best Practices Guide (http://opengeoportal.org/working-groups/metadata/) were also updated.
